            "body": "Thanks for the reply. I used `set sidescroll=0` and that seems to have made it act like vim now. Doing some more research it still doesn't reset back to column 0 with lines over a certain length\r\n![nvim_05](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/8584482/154592588-b8e19bad-6f91-4687-ade2-4cda1883f43c.png)\r\n![nvim_04](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/8584482/154592595-fe447868-9866-4d9e-b603-c533a6e8e2f7.png)\r\n![nvim_06](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/8584482/154592598-c6548568-89a5-4058-8485-d36675022793.png)\r\n\r\nHowever, this now acts exactly the same way as normal vim. So I don't know if you consider this a neovim bug or vim bug or both. \r\n\r\nI still don't think it should act like this because you want to see all of the code from the start of the line where possible. While you can see the entire line the cursor is on, you can't see all of some of the surrounding lines in the example I showed. \r\n",
